# ðŸŒŸ ECMAScript 2025: Next-Level JavaScript Features

ES2025 introduces transformative features to JavaScript, making code more expressive and efficient. This guide dives into each feature with code snippets and use cases.

## 1. Iterator Helpers

Chainable iterator methods for cleaner code:

```javascript
const numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];

// Traditional approach
const doubledOdds = numbers
  .filter(x => x % 2 === 1)
  .map(x => x * 2);

// With Iterator Helpers
const iterator = numbers.values()
  .filter(x => x % 2 === 1)
  .map(x => x * 2);

for (const num of iterator) {
  console.log(num); // 2, 6, 10
}

// Convert back to array
const result = Array.from(iterator);
```

**Supported Methods**: `map`, `filter`, `take`, `drop`, `flatMap`, `reduce`.

## 2. New Set Methods

Perform set operations efficiently:

```javascript
const frontend = new Set(['react', 'vue', 'angular']);
const backend = new Set(['node', 'python', 'java']);
const fullstack = new Set(['react', 'node']);

// Union: All unique elements
const allSkills = frontend.union(backend);
// Set {'react', 'vue', 'angular', 'node', 'python', 'java'}

// Intersection: Common elements
const common = frontend.intersection(fullstack);
// Set {'react'}

// Difference: Elements in first set but not in second
const frontendOnly = frontend.difference(fullstack);
// Set {'vue', 'angular'}

// Symmetric Difference: Elements in either set but not both
const uniqueToEach = frontend.symmetricDifference(backend);

// Subset check
const isSubset = fullstack.isSubsetOf(frontend); // false
const isSuperset = frontend.isSupersetOf(fullstack); // true

// Practical example: Skill matching
const requiredSkills = new Set(['javascript', 'react', 'node']);
const candidateSkills = new Set(['javascript', 'react', 'vue', 'css']);

const matchingSkills = candidateSkills.intersection(requiredSkills);
const missingSkills = requiredSkills.difference(candidateSkills);

console.log(`Matching: ${matchingSkills.size}/${requiredSkills.size}`);
console.log('Missing:', Array.from(missingSkills));
```

## 3. Array.prototype.findLast and findLastIndex

